## Section 5: Character Design Direction

**Visibility model:** Rimworld-style NPC abstraction — NPCs NOT permanently visible on main camera. Routes visualized via production chain arrows, not individual NPC sprites.

### 1. NPC Design Philosophy

**Two-tier system** — match art investment to screen presence.

| Tier | Use Case | Detail Level |
|------|----------|-------------|
| **Tier A: Brief Appearance** | Construction animation, recruitment, notification pop-up | Full sprites — walk/idle/work, 32x32 or 48x48 |
| **Tier B: Abstract Dot** | Main camera gameplay (95% of play time) | 8x8 solid color circle — not a sprite, just a colored marker |

**Philosophy:** *"The game is about the production chain, not the characters. Character detail is invested proportionally to screen presence."* — Optimization Over Expansion pillar applied to art.

### 2. Player Character

**Always visible, 32x32, most prominent shape.** Never abstracted.

| Role | Primary Color | Secondary | Tool Indicator |
|------|--------------|-----------|----------------|
| **Player** | Deep blue | Gold trim | Carries multiple tools (sack) |
| **Lumberjack** | Forest green | Brown | Axe (L-shape) |
| **Farmer** | Wheat yellow | Earth brown | Scythe (curve) |
| **Miner** | Charcoal grey | Stone tan | Pickaxe (cross) |
| **Builder** | Terracotta | Mortar white | Trowel |
| **Forager** | Berry red | Leaf green | Basket |

**Palette principle:** Natural medieval pigments only — all colors exist in the environment. No neon, no synthetic hues.

### 3. Role Communication Hierarchy

1. **Color** (fastest) — clothing palette per role, visible even at 8x8 pixel dot size
2. **Silhouette** — unique body/proportion profile per archetype
3. **Tool** (Tier A only) — reinforces role in brief appearances

### 4. LOD Philosophy

| LOD Level | Size | Detail | Usage |
|-----------|------|--------|-------|
| **LOD0: Full** | 32x32 | Full sprite sheet: idle (4f), walk (4f), work (3f/tool), 8 directions | Player always; NPCs only in Tier A moments |
| **LOD1: Abstract** | 8x8 | Solid color circle, no sprite | NPCs on main camera |
| **LOD2: Icon** | 16x16 | Single static pose, simplified | NPC selection panel, assignment UI, tooltips |

**80% sprite reduction** vs. full NPC sprite system.

---

## Section 6: Environment & Level Art

### 1. Architectural Style

**Minimalist Medieval** — authentic medieval shapes (timber frames, thatched roofs, cobblestone), flat-colored or simple pixel art. No fantasy-kitsch (no glowing crystals, no dragons), no hyper-realism.

**Building visual language:**
- **Manual-stage buildings:** Rough-hewn timber, thatched roofs, exposed beams, warm browns. Asymmetrical details — each building has slightly different timber placement (randomized per-instance during authoring).
- **Automated-stage buildings:** Clean geometric forms, stone foundations, metal accents (bell roofs, iron trim), white/silver accents. Symmetrical and precise.
- **Progression signal:** A lumber mill starts as a timber-frame shack with a manual saw. Once automated, it gains a stone chimney, metal gears, and white accent panels. The player *sees* automation.

### 2. Texture Philosophy

**Flat-colored pixel art with minimal shading.** 2-3 shade levels per color (base + shadow + highlight) — enough for depth perception, never enough to create visual noise at 60fps.

**No PBR, no normal maps.** TileMapLayer rendering with flat colors is sufficient for top-down 2D. Texture variation comes from palette swaps and tile set diversity, not surface detail.

**Pixel art anti-aliasing:** None. Hard edges only. Anti-aliasing is a 3D technique that looks wrong on pixel art at game scale.

### 3. Prop Density Rules

| Area Type | Prop Density | Examples | Rationale |
|-----------|-------------|----------|-----------|
| **Meadow (Early Game)** | Sparse — 1 prop per 10-15 tiles | Wild berry bushes, lone trees, small rock clusters | Natural, untouched landscape |
| **Construction Zone** | Medium — 1 prop per 5-8 tiles | Felled stumps, stacked wood piles, dirt paths | Active building creates localized clutter |
| **Automated Production** | Low — 1 prop per 20+ tiles | Only functional props (chutes, hoppers, storage bins) | Clean, efficient — optimization over volume |
| **Settlement Hub** | Medium — 1 prop per 5-8 tiles | Benches, wells, market stalls, fences | Social center, but not cluttered |

**Rule:** Never place decorative props in a player's direct line of sight along a production chain flow line. Decorations compete with chain readability.

---

## Section 7: UI/HUD Visual Direction

### 1. HUD Architecture: Asymmetric Screen-Space Panels

Pure diegetic UI won't work for production chain management. Screen-space panels are required, styled to feel integrated with the world.

**Panel layout:**
```
┌──────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┐
│  Game World (main viewport)                              │
│                                                          │
│                                              ┌─────────┐ │
│  ┌─────┐  ┌─────┐  ┌─────┐                   │Production│ │
│  │Wheat│→│Mill │→│Bakery│                   │  Chains  │ │
│  └─────┘  └─────┘  └─────┘                   │  [◻]   │ │
│                                              └─────────┘ │
├──────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┤
│  ⚡ Energy ████████████░░░░  72%    [Day 7, Tick 14/30] │
│  Inv  [🌾][🍞][🪓][🪨][  ]     3/5 items                 │
└──────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┘
```

- **Right panel:** Production chain dashboard (most-used info, natural reading end-position)
- **Bottom-left:** Energy bar + trage inventory (persistent need-to-know, out of primary view)
- **Bottom-center:** Day/time display (low-frequency, always visible)
- **Top-right:** Notification toasts (edge of screen, doesn't interfere)

### 2. Iconography: Outlined Line-Art

- **2px stroke width, 16px grid**
- **Neutral charcoal** (`#2A2A2A` or `#8B8B8B`) — semantic color appears only on accents (energy bar, status dots), NOT on icons themselves
- **Why not illustrated pixel art?** Requires ~3x more design work, won't read at small sizes, creates visual noise in dense UI

### 3. Typography

**Font:** Silkscreen (or similar geometric pixel font)

**Hierarchy:**

| Role | Size | Weight | Use Case |
|------|------|--------|----------|
| Panel Title | 20px | Bold | "Production Chains", "Resources" |
| Label | 16px | Medium | "Wheat → Flour", "Efficiency" |
| Data Value | 16px | Regular | "87%", "3/5", "12/day" |
| Secondary | 14px* | Regular | "Waits for wheat", "2 pending" |
| Notification | 14px | Regular | Toast messages |
| Tooltip | 14px* | Regular | Per-building hover |

*\*Upgraded from 12px per UX review — 12px Silkscreen is borderline unreadable and causes reading fatigue.*

**Accessibility:** 3 discrete font sizes (Small/Medium/Large), NOT continuous slider. Pixel fonts don't scale smoothly — discrete steps keep them crisp.

### 4. Animation Direction

**"Functional, not decorative."**

| Trigger | Animation | Duration | Easing |
|---------|-----------|----------|--------|
| Panel appear/disappear | Slide-in from edge | 120ms | ease-out |
| Production step status change | Color transition (no movement) | 80ms | linear |
| Bottleneck highlight | Color pulse | 600ms loop | ease-in-out |
| Energy bar depletion | Smooth fill reduction | 200ms | ease-out |
| Notification toast | Slide-in + hold 3s + slide-out | 3800ms total | ease-out |
| Production arrow flow | Dot traveling along chain line | 400ms repeat | linear loop |

**No spring/overshoot animations.** UI is data-dense. Animated panels that bounce make reading feel like waiting.

**Performance constraint:** Max 4 simultaneous UI animations. Use `CanvasItem` transforms, NOT shaders. Batch all production arrow dots into a single CanvasGroup (1 draw call).

### 5. UX Alignment: Key Conflicts Resolved

| Conflict | Resolution |
|----------|-----------|
| Color-only status indicators | Every color has a shape/icon backup (triangle=error, checkmark=success) |
| Build ghost visibility on pixel terrain | 2px outline + grid overlay, green=valid, red=invalid |
| Bottleneck urgency vs. non-intrusive | Tiered system: persistent badge on production chain panel, not just toasts |
| Pixel font readability at 12px | Minimum 14px for all body/secondary text |
| Animation budget impact | Cap at 4 simultaneous, batch production dots, pause when FPS < 55 |
| Colorblind access | No semantic meaning relies on color alone; full icon+text backup |

---

## Section 8: Asset Standards

### 1. File Format & Organization

**Core philosophy:** Atlas-first for static geometry, sprite sheet for animation, individual sprites only where layout flexibility demands it.

| Category | Format | Atlas Size | Reason |
|----------|--------|------------|--------|
| Ground tiles | Texture atlas (PNG) | 256x256 (8x8 grid of 32px) | 1 draw call for entire ground layer |
| Building tiles | Texture atlas (PNG) | 512x512 | All buildings share palette |
| Props/foliage | Texture atlas (PNG) | 256x256 | Shared earthy palette |
| Characters | Sprite sheets (PNG) | 128x128 to 256x256 | Rows = directions, columns = frames |
| UI elements | Texture atlas (PNG) | 512x512 | All UI controls in one draw call |
| VFX/particles | Texture atlas (PNG) | 128x128 max per effect | 5 atlases max total |
| Individual sprites | PNG | 32x32 to 64x64 | Unique props under 30 for MVP |

**Naming convention:**
```
atlas_[purpose].png               # Atlas files (ground, buildings, props, ui, vfx)
char_[name]_animation.png          # Character sprite sheets
env_tile_[name]_[id].png          # Individual tile images (before atlas assembly)
env_shadow_[name].png             # Ground contact shadows
vfx_[effect]_[frame|atlas].png    # Particle textures
```

### 2. Resolution Tiers

| Category | Base Size | Max Size | Notes |
|----------|-----------|----------|-------|
| Ground tiles | 32x32 | 32x32 | Fixed — consistency over variety |
| Building tiles | 32x32/cell | Up to 128x128 | Multi-tile buildings in Core Experience |
| Characters | 32x32 | 64x64 | NPCs at 32px, player at 64px |
| Props | 32x32 | 64x64 | Small for readability at camera distance |
| VFX | 32x32 | 128x128 | Larger for particle systems |
| UI icons | 16x16 | 32x32 | High detail at close range |

**Golden rule:** Every sprite snaps cleanly to a 32px grid. No 33px, 47px, or 51px sprites.

### 3. Godot 4.6 Pixel Art Import Settings (NON-NEGOTIABLE)

Every sprite texture in Godot 4.6 import must have:

```
Filter:     Nearest (no bilinear/trilinear — this ruins pixel art)
Mipmaps:    Disabled (cause aliasing and shimmering)
Compression: Lossless PNG (not VCS/SVT — artifacts on pixel edges)
Wrap Mode:  Clamp to edge (prevents texture bleeding at tile boundaries)
SRGB:       Disabled (handled in material, not import)
Normal Map: Disabled
```

**One exception:** Particle textures use `Filter: Linear` (GPUParticles2D needs smooth blending).

**Enforcement:** Create a custom Godot import preset that auto-applies these settings to all `.png` files in `assets/art/`.

### 4. Performance Budgets

**Draw Call Budget (< 1000):**

| Element | Draw Calls |
|---------|-----------|
| Ground TileMapLayer | 1 |
| Ground Detail Layer | 1 |
| Building TileMapLayer | 1 |
| Prop/Foliage Layer | 1 |
| Sprite2D instances (~50-80) | ~30-50 (batched by atlas) |
| UI layer | ~3-5 |
| Particle systems (3-5) | 3-5 |
| **Total (MVP, full map)** | **~45-65** |

TileMapLayer batches all tiles from the same atlas into a single draw call. At 45-65 DC, the game uses ~5-6% of the budget even with a 30x30 map and full MVP content.

**Memory Budget (512MB soft):**

| Textures | Size |
|----------|------|
| All atlases (ground, buildings, props, ui, vfx) | ~3.5 MB |
| Individual sprites (~30) | ~256 KB |
| Character animation sheets (~10) | ~1.5 MB |
| **Total** | **~5.3 MB** |

Texture memory is trivially small. The real constraint is draw call batching, not memory.

**Instance budget:** 100-200 visible Sprite2D instances at any time. All batched by shared atlas texture.

### 5. TileMapLayer Architecture (Recommended, bottom to top)

```
Layer 0: Ground tiles (grass, dirt, water, roads)
Layer 1: Ground details (grass tufts, cracks, pebbles) — same atlas as Layer 0
Layer 2: Building floors/walls
Layer 3: Building details (doors, windows, roofs) — same atlas as Layer 2
Layer 4: Props and foliage
Layer 5: Overhead props (trees above buildings, hanging decorations)
Layer 6: Dynamic entities (player, NPCs) — Sprite2D nodes, not tiles
Layer 7: UI overlay (indicators, tooltips, placement preview)
```

**Maximum:** 8-10 TileMapLayers. More than 15 risks render order bugs with no performance benefit.

### 6. Material Constraints

- **Sprite2D:** 1 material slot per sprite (`material` property). No multi-material sprites — use texture regions from atlases.
- **TileSet:** 1 texture per TileSet. Max 100+ tile variations per TileSet from a single atlas.
- **Custom shaders:** Not needed for MVP. Reserved for: seasonal palette swap, water shimmer, day/night overlay.

### 7. Draw Call Rules

1. Never put tiles from different atlases on the same TileMapLayer
2. Never use Sprite2D for atlas-boundable content
3. Every unique texture = potential new draw call. Keep unique textures under 25
4. Each ParticleProcessMaterial = 1 draw call. Cap at 5 visible simultaneously
5. UI: batch all icons into the UI atlas. No individual texture files for UI icons.

